'''Willoughby Ions''' (1881-1977) was an American composer, artist, poet and dramatist. She was an Art administrator, for the [[Federal Art Project]].

==Life==
Born Estelle de Willoughby Ions in [[New Orleans]], she was married twice.
She wrote the play, "The Age of Innocents," and opera "All in a Golden Springtime".
She was a member of the [[Equal Suffrage League of Virginia]].<ref>http://www.outhistory.org/wiki/The_Social_and_Cultural_Elite_and_the_Hidden_%E2%80%9CGay%E2%80%9D_Society</ref>
She was a partner of [[Ad<U+00E8>le Clark]].<ref>{{cite book| url=http://books.google.com/books?id=9MMAg_NnwQUC&pg=PA14&dq=%22willoughby+ions%22&hl=en&ei=9wDTTvrMBtH5sQLq8aDdDg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=%22willoughby%20ions%22&f=false| title=Lesbian and Gay Richmond| authors=Beth Marschak, Alex Lorch| publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year= 2008| isbn= 978-0-7385-5368-9}}</ref>
Her papers are held at the [[Virginia Historical Society]].<ref>http://www.vahistorical.org/arvfind/goodman.htm</ref>

